                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>St Thomas</placeName>
                                        <date>2 July 1847</date> private</p>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revd Mr Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <placeName>Phila</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">Dr Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">Your letter of <date>12 Nov, 11 Dec 4 Jany</date>
                                        are<lb/> before me I would have been[?] replied to before
                                        this but really I<lb/> have been am still so occupied that I
                                        could not spare time<lb/> before, the affairs of our
                                        Congregation have been extremely<lb/> heavy for me as you
                                        shall find, I will firstly reply to your<lb/> letter of
                                                  <date>Dec.</date> You are quite correct when you
                                        state that I<lb/> am interested for you. I have always been,
                                        am so still, this<lb/> has been the reason of my always
                                        writing you in the <sic>stile</sic> I do.<lb/> I regret to
                                        find that you had been so indisposed. I <sic>hurt</sic>
                                        that<lb/> your health has since been perfectly
                                        re-established.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Mr Nans.[?]</persName> and myself are at
                                        variance, because at<lb/> his arrival I placed every
                                        confidence in him as an old friend<lb/> a man being alike
                                        friendly to myself as well as to the party<lb/> appeared to
                                        me, one to when I considered devoted the duty of<lb/>
                                        interfering reconciling all the evils of the
                                        <sic>hart</sic>, but in<lb/> stead of that<lb/> he
                                        inserted[?] himself under the banner and did<lb/> all he
                                        could to annoy vex <del>him</del> me, being then in
                                        appearance<lb/> friendly disposed, he concocted a letter
                                        which <persName>Dr Peixotto</persName> signed as
                                        President<lb/> Addressed to the head of the Commission for
                                        framing the new laws<lb/> in which he reviled me shamefully.
                                        I attacked him upon it<lb/> he acknowledged it; for this
                                        other reasons I withdrew from him<lb/> not only myself but
                                        other highly respectable members of the<lb/> congregation
                                        lost the opinion they held of him, he then became<lb/> a
                                        leader of the party; continued to do all he could to
                                        annoy,<lb/> this led him to be in[?] agreement <persName>M
                                                  Nathan</persName> as well as to<lb/> myself,
                                        making use of no measured language, calling him a<lb/>
                                        Counting Priest c.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I have written you so fully in the benefits</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>of confirmation that I will add what has really come<lb/> under my
                                        notice, there was 3 entire families here, who
                                        previously<lb/> to <persName>Mr Carillons [?]</persName>,
                                        were on the eve of apostatizing, his<lb/> instructions for
                                        the confirmation private arguments completely<lb/> brought
                                        them back to their duty. I have since had the pleasure<lb/>
                                        of beholding its Moral Religious effects upon the Young<lb/>
                                        people who now venerate their religion because they begin
                                        to<lb/> understand it. it is only a few whose opinions are
                                        lax<lb/> and are desirous of helping their children in
                                        ignorance of true<lb/> religion that are so violently
                                        opposed to it because they are<lb/> afraid that their
                                        children will reproach them for not keeping<lb/> the
                                                  <date>Sabbath</date> holy days which is strictly
                                        enforced in the<lb/> Catechism, the proof that it is well
                                        received is, that <persName>Mr<lb/> Nathan</persName> will
                                        confirm 14 young people in <date>Passover</date>. I am
                                        sorry<lb/> that we do not agree upon this point, for
                                        experience has confined<lb/> my opinion of its benefits I am
                                        resolved to promote it with<lb/> all my might. <persName>Mr
                                                  Nathan</persName> would have replied but the<lb/>
                                        man has been so annoyed by the conduct of
                                                  <persName>Simmonds</persName> his<lb/> party that
                                        I do not for the life of me know how he could<lb/> get thro'
                                        his duties as well as he did, added to it, we<lb/> have a
                                        heavy task to get through the new laws, the heaviest<lb/>
                                        part falling upon himself myself;–I saw him last night,<lb/>
                                        he promises to reply very soon.–By the Bye I have never<lb/>
                                        secured the Occident for <date>September</date>. Please to
                                        forward it.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I now come to our Congregational Matters under
                                        the<lb/> Administration of <persName>Simmonds</persName> his
                                        friends. I informed you of<lb/> the abuses of power in some
                                        cases, these continued so<lb/> long, new ones were added
                                        that enacted[?] a great stir in the<lb/> Congregation very
                                        many that had been opposed to me, now<lb/> saw that the
                                        reports they were against me were false; at<lb/> length
                                                  <persName>Simmonds</persName> quitted the Island
                                        for the purpose of<lb/> marrying her Brother with a lady at
                                                  <placeName><sic>Caracao </sic></placeName>, by
                                        which the</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>the administration of the Synagogue was only left in the<lb/> hands
                                        of 4 instead of 7 persons—5 of the body forming a<lb/>
                                        quorum, two of the members at the election refused to act
                                        <lb/> never did as long as the Quorum was complete no one
                                        opposed<lb/> the legality.–but at
                                                  <persName>Simmonds</persName> leaving, he with the
                                        4 others<lb/> balloted [?] out of 2 instead of 4 Wardens as
                                        the law orders<lb/> to fill the place of President; now
                                        previous to balloting for<lb/> a new the old President must
                                        resign, as soon as he did<lb/> this, the body was reduced to
                                        4 which were not a quorum <lb/> had not the power of doing
                                        any business, consequently the<lb/> balloting was illegal;
                                        the most respectable members of<lb/> the Congregation
                                        represented the business to [?] showed<lb/> the necessity of
                                        the Government of the Congregation being filled<lb/> up of a
                                        new election for that purpose (the laws of the<lb/>
                                        Congregation does not provide for such a state of
                                        things,)<lb/> the Government who knew I were heartily
                                        disgusted with<lb/> all the proceedings of the entire party
                                        since the affair<lb/> with <persName>Carellion</persName>
                                        who saw how every thing had gone to [?]<lb/>[?], who know
                                        that these people were improper ones to<lb/> be in the
                                        Government, appointed me President Messrs<lb/> O[?]
                                                  <persName>Fidangree[?]</persName> Wardens, then
                                        ordered an entire new<lb/> election of 7. this the 4
                                        Remaining of <persName>Simmonds</persName>
                                        Administration<lb/> protested against, as the were the
                                        majority I could not carry<lb/> out the Government order, I
                                        informed Government of it sent in<lb/> the protest, the
                                        Governor immediately dismissed them from their<lb/> offices
                                        placed <persName>Miss Rothschild</persName>, <persName>Dr
                                                  DeCortz</persName>, <persName>Dr
                                                  Monsato</persName><lb/>
                                        <persName>Isaac Pritt[?]</persName> in their stead the Board
                                        to continue until<lb/> further orders:–we found the affairs
                                        in a very bad <lb/> neglected state, the circular they
                                        published was proved to be<lb/> incorrect in all its parts,
                                        the Synagogue was in need of repair<lb/> the [?] at the
                                        Burial Ground in a very bad state, and<lb/> [?] the minister
                                        every other officer in credit. The Minister</p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p>for 6 months pay as well as the other officers, we required<lb/>
                                        $1200 over above the Taxes to make the Synagogue clear,<lb/>
                                        in consequence we determined to call a meeting of the<lb/>
                                        congregation lay before the members an expose (I could<lb/>
                                        get the sum required by [?] pay $250 per year) previous<lb/>
                                        to having any idea of calling a general meeting, I
                                        wrote<lb/> a letter to <persName>Nans</persName> proposing a
                                        reconciliation of all that had<lb/> passed asking him to use
                                        his influence with those over<lb/> whom I know he had
                                        influence to forget bury the past<lb/> remote[?] for the
                                        general good. I did this for the common<lb/> good, with no
                                        view to my particular standing, because I<lb/> was already
                                        at the head of the Congregation placed there by<lb/>
                                        government, consequently not in need of the suffrages
                                        of<lb/> any one—the act was purely religious—his reply was
                                        of<lb/> a nature that in time will make him feel regret
                                        a<lb/> refusal; except upon terms that could never have
                                        been<lb/> acceded to by any will in either of the
                                        congregation, he<lb/> wanted us to go back—only have Readers
                                        without pulpit<lb/> instruction, to do away with Taxes
                                        substitute offerings<lb/> to them upon the religiously
                                        inclined the whole <sic>burthen</sic> of<lb/> maintaining
                                        the establishment, at length the meeting<lb/> took place at
                                        that meeting he and the arguments quoted<lb/> which was met
                                        by a vote of 3 to 1, against him, his party<lb/> of 10
                                        persons, he promises that affairs shall be worse than</p>
                              <pb n="5"/>
                              <p>ever, then you see his conduct, the Governor being very<lb/> much
                                        displeased with his <del>his</del> party' doings did not
                                        invite<lb/> any one of them to a Ball he gave for some Dutch
                                        Naval<lb/> Officers, this has made him more furious, but
                                        thank God<lb/> he cannot injure altho he may annoy, you can
                                        form no<lb/> idea of the trouble I have had to re-arrange
                                        the affairs.<lb/> the Synagogue is under repair, the Burial
                                        House will be, the<lb/> people beg me to pay their taxes.
                                                  <persName>Mr Nathan</persName> has consented<lb/>
                                        to leave his Salary in a little time the Sunday School
                                        will<lb/> be again alone—in spite of the distractions</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Pray send me the [?] Volume of the Pentateuch
                                        in<lb/> place of the one that was injured returned we shall
                                        soon<lb/> require it. The new Laws will go into Government
                                        in the<lb/> Month. I have no time to recapitulate all the
                                        insults to<lb/>
                                        <persName>Mr Nathan</persName>, <persName>Mr Bay</persName>
                                        had a circumcision at his house, he<lb/> wrote to inform me
                                        stated that he did not require the<lb/> services of the
                                        Minister, insulting him thus publicly.
                                                  <persName>Bay</persName> is<lb/>
                                        <persName>Naan</persName> son in law</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I regret to state that my son
                                                  <persName>Moses</persName> has been<lb/> obliged
                                        to take his name off of the list of subscribers to the<lb/>
                                        Occident for the ensuing Year, business having gone bad
                                        with<lb/> him, 3d [?] <persName>Naan</persName> refused to
                                        pay his tax yesterday. I<lb/> will not enforce it by law as
                                        I am determined to do the<lb/> opposite of that which he
                                        party desire. I will be moderate<lb/> put up with their
                                        opposition as far as I can without<lb/> creating more bad
                                        feeling, it is awful to live among such<lb/> bad
                                        spirits;–you can suppose that neither himself for any
                                        of<lb/> his party of 10 came to the Synagogue, they cannot
                                        be accused<lb/> of having done often previously–</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">With best wishes I am My Dr Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">Yours truly</p>
                              <p rend="indent(4)">
                                        <persName role="author">A Wolff</persName>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="6"/>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revd Mr Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <placeName>Philada</placeName>
                              </p>
                    </body>
